<h2>3. Core Concepts</h2>

<h3>3.1 Injector</h3>
<p>
  A scope container that holds <em>providers</em> and forms a parent-child hierarchy.
  Injectors can target DOM elements (<code>HTMLInjector</code>) or ES Modules (<code>ModuleInjector</code>).
  Lookup traverses the parent chain until a provider is found or the root is reached.
</p>

<h3>3.2 Provider</h3>
<p>
  A named value or registry stored on an injector, keyed by a string.
  Providers may be plain objects, registry instances (e.g., <code>CustomElementRegistry</code>),
  or context instances (e.g., <code>CustomContext</code>).
</p>

<h3>3.3 Consumer</h3>
<p>
  Code that requests a provider by key. The injector system tracks consumers
  via <code>WeakRef</code> to avoid memory leaks and support dynamic provider swapping.
</p>

<h3>3.4 Consumable</h3>
<p>
  A multi-resolving async primitive returned by <code>consume()</code>.
  Consumable is simultaneously:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Promise-compatible</strong> — supports <code>await consumable</code> for one-shot resolution</li>
  <li><strong>AsyncIterator-compatible</strong> — supports <code>for await (const { value } of consumable)</code> for reactive watching</li>
  <li><strong>Multi-resolving</strong> — <code>provide(value)</code> can be called multiple times, each time resolving the current pending promise and creating a new one</li>
</ul>
<pre><code>// One-shot
const { value } = await consumable;

// Reactive
for await (const { value } of consumable) {
  update(value);
}

// Rejection (provider removed)
consumable.reject(new Error('Provider disposed'));
</code></pre>

<h3>3.5 Injector Chain</h3>
<p>
  The ordered sequence of injectors from a consumer's location up to the root.
  For DOM injectors, this follows the ancestor element chain.
  For module injectors, this follows the module's declared parent.
</p>

<h3>3.6 Scope Types</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Scope</th><th>Injector Type</th><th>Target</th><th>Querier Validation</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DOM scope</td>
    <td><code>HTMLInjector</code></td>
    <td><code>HTMLElement | RootNode | Comment</code></td>
    <td><code>target.contains(querier)</code> — DOM subtree containment</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Module scope</td>
    <td><code>ModuleInjector</code></td>
    <td><code>ImportMeta</code></td>
    <td>Always valid — modules don't have containment hierarchy</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>3.7 Provider Lifecycle</h3>
<pre><code>Created        → injector.set(key, provider)
  ↓
Claimed        → claim(provider) notifies existing consumers
  ↓
Updated        → consumable.provide(newValue) — triggers await/for-await
  ↓
Disposed       → consumable.reject(error) — exits for-await loops
                  injector.delete(key) + unclaim(provider)
</code></pre>

<hr>

<h2>4. Provider Type Map</h2>
<p>
  The Provider Type Map is a normative registry of known provider key patterns and their corresponding
  registry constructors. This table is used by:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>The runtime API for type inference</li>
  <li>The TypeScript <code>ProviderTypeMap</code> interface for typed lookups</li>
  <li>Future transformers for registry instantiation in DSL desugaring</li>
</ul>
<table>
  <tr><th>Key Pattern</th><th>Registry Constructor</th><th>Status</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customElements</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomElementRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Scoped custom element definitions</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customContextTypes</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomContextRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Context type constructors</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customAttributes</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomAttributeRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Custom attribute behaviors</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customExpressionParsers</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomExpressionParserRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Expression parser pipeline</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customTextNodeParsers</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomTextNodeParserRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Text node type detection</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customTextNodes</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomTextNodeRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Text node implementations</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customStores</code></td>
    <td><code>CustomStoreRegistry</code></td>
    <td>Concept</td>
    <td>State management stores</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>customContexts:<em>name</em></code></td>
    <td>Direct provider (no registry)</td>
    <td>Implemented</td>
    <td>Set directly on injector by key</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  Keys not matching a known pattern are treated as <strong>direct providers</strong> —
  the value is stored and retrieved as-is, with no registry intermediary.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>5. Provide Semantics</h2>

<h3>5.0 Provide is a Declaration, Not a Load</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Critical design principle:</strong> A <code>provide</code> statement does <strong>not</strong> import or execute a module.
  It registers a mapping from a provider key to a module location (or value), similar to how
  <code>&lt;script type="importmap"&gt;</code> declares where bare specifiers resolve without loading them.
</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Construct</th><th>What It Does</th><th>When Loading Happens</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>import x from './mod'</code></td>
    <td>Loads, links, and executes the module</td>
    <td>Before the importing module's body runs</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>&lt;script type="importmap"&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Declares where bare specifiers resolve</td>
    <td>Never — only resolves when an <code>import</code> references the specifier</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>provide X as 'key'</code></td>
    <td>Declares that <code>'key'</code> resolves to <code>X</code> within this injector scope</td>
    <td>Never — only loads when a <code>consume</code> references the key</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  This means an injector block can declare a complete map of every possible provider and their locations
  without incurring any loading cost. Only when a module issues a <code>consume</code> does the system
  resolve and load the actual dependency tree.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Bundler optimization:</strong> Because both <code>provide</code> and <code>consume</code> are declarative
  (like <code>import</code> statements), a bundler can statically analyze the full dependency graph at build time.
  It can determine which providers are actually consumed, inline or chunk them, and eliminate the async
  resolution overhead entirely — producing the same kind of optimized output that bundlers produce for
  static <code>import</code> statements today.
</p>

<p>
  Three prepositions control the provide semantics:
</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Preposition</th><th>Semantics</th><th>Registry Behavior</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>as</code></td>
    <td><strong>Replace</strong> — creates or replaces the provider at this key</td>
    <td>A new registry is created with the provided entries</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>in</code></td>
    <td><strong>Extend</strong> — merges entries into the existing provider</td>
    <td>Get existing registry (or create new), then define entries into it</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>from</code></td>
    <td><strong>Source</strong> — specifies where the provider comes from</td>
    <td>Used with <code>as</code>/<code>in</code> or alone for re-providing</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>5.1 Replace (<code>as</code>)</h3>
<p>Creates or replaces the provider at the specified key.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>provide MyStore as 'customContexts:state';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>injector.set('customContexts:state', MyStore);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>With registry entries (names must be explicit):</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>provide { 'my-button': Button, 'my-input': Input } as 'customElements';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const registry = new CustomElementRegistry();
registry.define('my-button', Button);
registry.define('my-input', Input);
injector.set('customElements', registry);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>5.2 Extend (<code>in</code>)</h3>
<p>Merges entries into an existing registry, or creates one if none exists.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>provide { 'my-button': Button } in 'customElements';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const registry = injector.get('customElements') ?? new CustomElementRegistry();
registry.define('my-button', Button);
injector.set('customElements', registry);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>Design note:</strong> The <code>in</code> desugaring uses get-or-create + define.
  No new runtime API method is needed — the existing <code>get()</code>, <code>set()</code>,
  and registry <code>define()</code> methods suffice.
</p>

<h3>5.3 Re-provide from Source (<code>from</code>)</h3>
<p>Copies providers from another injector into the current scope.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>// All providers
provide * from import.injector;

// Selected providers
provide { 'customElements', 'customAttributes' } from import.injector;</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>// All providers
for (const [key, provider] of parentInjector.entries()) {
  injector.set(key, provider);
}

// Selected providers
for (const key of ['customElements', 'customAttributes']) {
  const provider = parentInjector.get(key);
  if (provider) injector.set(key, provider);
}</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>5.4 Provide from URL (Deferred)</h3>
<pre><code>provide * from 'https://lib.company.com/shared';</code></pre>
<p>
  <strong>Status:</strong> Deferred to Phase 2.
  Requires dynamic <code>import()</code> combined with injector binding.
  The semantics of what is "provided" from a URL (module exports? a manifest?) need further design.
</p>

<h3>5.5 Naming Rules</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Provider key names are always quoted strings: <code>'customElements'</code>, <code>'customContexts:nav'</code></li>
  <li>Registry entry names must be explicit in Phase 1: <code>'my-button': Button</code></li>
  <li>Convention-based name inference (PascalCase to kebab-case) is planned for Phase 2 via <code>provide class</code> — single-word names that produce no hyphen are a compile-time error (see Open Question #4)</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>6. Consume Semantics</h2>
<p>
  The <code>consume</code> statement requests a provider from the injector chain.
  How it resolves depends on where it appears:
</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Context</th><th>Resolution</th><th>Access</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Inside an <code>injector</code> block (DSL)</strong></td>
    <td>Async resolution happens <em>before</em> the block body runs — the transformer builds the dependency graph from all <code>provide</code>/<code>consume</code> declarations and prefetches in parallel</td>
    <td><strong>Synchronous</strong> — consumed values are available immediately, like <code>import</code> bindings</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Imperative code (Runtime API)</strong></td>
    <td>Dynamic — the system cannot know the dependency tree ahead of time</td>
    <td><strong>Asynchronous</strong> — returns a <code>Consumable&lt;T&gt;</code> that resolves when the provider is available</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  The DSL <code>consume</code> gives the same guarantee as <code>import</code>: everything is resolved before your code runs.
  The Runtime API <code>consume()</code> gives you the <code>Consumable</code> async primitive because it cannot make that guarantee.
</p>

<h3>6.1 Basic Consume</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>consume nav from 'customContexts:nav';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const nav = injector.consume('customContexts:nav', this);
// nav: Consumable&lt;NavigationContext&gt;</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>6.2 Destructured Consume</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>consume { nav, redux } from 'customContexts';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const nav = injector.consume('customContexts:nav', this);
const redux = injector.consume('customContexts:redux', this);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  Each destructured name becomes a separate consume call.
  The key is constructed by appending <code>:<em>name</em></code> to the source string.
</p>

<h3>6.3 Path Expression Consume</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>consume { 'foo.bar[0]' as item } from 'customContexts:data';</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const item = injector.consume('customContexts:data/foo.bar[0]', this);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  The path expression is appended after a <code>/</code> separator.
  If the resolved provider implements the <code>Queryable</code> interface
  (<code>query(expression): Consumable</code>), the path expression is delegated to it.
  Otherwise the whole provider is returned.
</p>

<h3>6.4 Resolution Model: DSL vs Runtime</h3>

<h4>DSL: Synchronous Access (Inside Injector Blocks)</h4>
<p>
  When <code>consume</code> appears inside an <code>injector</code> block, the transformer can see all
  <code>provide</code> and <code>consume</code> statements statically. It builds the full dependency graph,
  prefetches all consumed modules in parallel, and makes consumed values available synchronously
  when the block body executes — exactly like ES module <code>import</code> bindings.
</p>
<pre><code>// DSL — consumed values are synchronous
injector AppScope {
  provide DateFnsAdapter as '@date/core';
  consume { format } from '@date/core';

  // 'format' is available here synchronously,
  // just like an import binding.
  const title = format(new Date(), 'MMMM yyyy');
}</code></pre>
<p>
  The async resolution phase (fetching modules, resolving the tree) happens <em>before</em> the block body runs.
  This is not fundamentally different from how <code>import</code> works — there is an async loading/linking phase,
  then synchronous access. A bundler can statically analyze this and eliminate the async phase entirely.
</p>

<h4>Runtime API: Asynchronous Access (Imperative Code)</h4>
<p>
  In imperative code, <code>consume()</code> returns a <code>Consumable&lt;T&gt;</code> — not a resolved value — for three reasons:
</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>No static analysis:</strong> The runtime cannot see the full dependency tree ahead of time, so it cannot prefetch and pre-resolve.</li>
  <li><strong>Reactive consumption:</strong> The <code>for await...of</code> protocol enables watching for provider changes over time. An awaited value would be a snapshot, losing reactivity.</li>
  <li><strong>Deferred resolution:</strong> A provider may not exist yet when <code>consume()</code> is called. The Consumable resolves when a matching provider is registered via the claim/unclaim system.</li>
</ol>
<pre><code>// Runtime API — consumed values are async
class MyElement extends HTMLElement {
  #nav = injector.consume('customContexts:nav', this);

  async connectedCallback() {
    // One-shot
    const { value: nav } = await this.#nav;

    // Or reactive
    for await (const { value: nav } of this.#nav) {
      this.render(nav);
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

<h4>Summary</h4>
<table>
  <tr><th></th><th>DSL (<code>consume</code> in injector block)</th><th>Runtime API (<code>injector.consume()</code>)</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Resolution</strong></td>
    <td>Static — transformer builds dependency graph</td>
    <td>Dynamic — resolved at call time</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Loading phase</strong></td>
    <td>Async, before block body runs (like <code>import</code>)</td>
    <td>Async, returns <code>Consumable</code></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Access</strong></td>
    <td>Synchronous</td>
    <td>Asynchronous (<code>await</code> or <code>for await</code>)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Bundler optimization</strong></td>
    <td>Full — can inline, chunk, tree-shake</td>
    <td>Limited — dynamic calls are opaque to bundlers</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<hr>

<h2>7. Injector Block Declaration</h2>
<p>
  The <code>injector</code> block declares a named injector scope containing
  <code>provide</code> and <code>consume</code> statements.
</p>

<h3>7.1 Named Block</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>injector AppScope {
  provide * from import.injector;
  provide { 'my-button': Button } as 'customElements';
  provide AppStore as 'customContexts:state';
}</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const AppScope = new Injector('AppScope');
for (const [k, v] of parentInjector.entries()) AppScope.set(k, v);
const reg = new CustomElementRegistry();
reg.define('my-button', Button);
AppScope.set('customElements', reg);
AppScope.set('customContexts:state', AppStore);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>7.2 Inheritance (<code>extends</code>)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>injector TestScope extends AppScope {
  provide { 'my-button': MockButton } as 'customElements';
}</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const TestScope = new Injector('TestScope');
TestScope.parentInjector = AppScope;
const reg = new CustomElementRegistry();
reg.define('my-button', MockButton);
TestScope.set('customElements', reg);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>Important:</strong> <code>extends</code> establishes a parent-chain relationship,
  not a copy of providers. <code>TestScope</code> inherits from <code>AppScope</code> via lookup —
  any provider not overridden in <code>TestScope</code> is resolved from <code>AppScope</code>.
</p>

<h3>7.3 Isolation (<code>isolate</code>)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Syntax</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>DSL</td>
    <td><pre><code>injector Sandbox isolate {
  provide SandboxStore as 'customContexts:state';
  // No parent — all providers must be explicit
}</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Runtime</td>
    <td><pre><code>const Sandbox = new Injector('Sandbox');
// parentInjector remains null
Sandbox.set('customContexts:state', SandboxStore);</code></pre></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p><code>extends</code> and <code>isolate</code> are mutually exclusive.</p>

<h3>7.4 Anonymous Block</h3>
<pre><code>// DSL
injector {
  provide * from import.injector;
}

// Runtime — no name needed
const scope = new Injector();
for (const [k, v] of parentInjector.entries()) scope.set(k, v);</code></pre>

<h3>7.5 Consume Inside Injector Blocks</h3>
<p>
  When <code>consume</code> appears inside an <code>injector</code> block, it has different semantics
  than in imperative code. The injector block is fully declarative — the transformer can see every
  <code>provide</code> and <code>consume</code> statement statically, build the complete dependency graph,
  and resolve all dependencies <em>before</em> the block body executes.
</p>
<pre><code>// DSL — consume inside an injector block
injector AppScope {
  provide DateFnsAdapter as '@date/core';
  provide FloatingUIDOM   as '@ui/floating';

  // These are resolved before the block body runs
  consume { format }       from '@date/core';
  consume { useFloating }  from '@ui/floating';

  // Consumed values are synchronous — like import bindings
  provide AppCalendar as 'customElements:hollow-calendar';
}</code></pre>
<p>The transformer desugars this to:</p>
<pre><code>// Compiled output — async resolution wrapped around synchronous body
const AppScope = await (async () => {
  const scope = new Injector('AppScope');
  scope.set('@date/core', DateFnsAdapter);
  scope.set('@ui/floating', FloatingUIDOM);

  // Resolve consumed dependencies
  const { format } = await scope.get('@date/core');
  const { useFloating } = await scope.get('@ui/floating');

  scope.set('customElements:hollow-calendar', AppCalendar);
  return scope;
})();</code></pre>
<p>
  <strong>Key insight:</strong> The async resolution phase is invisible to the developer.
  Inside the block, consumed values appear synchronous — exactly like <code>import</code> bindings
  appear synchronous even though module loading is async.
  A bundler can analyze the provide/consume declarations at build time and eliminate the
  async resolution entirely, inlining or chunking the resolved modules.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Contrast with Runtime API:</strong> In imperative code, <code>injector.consume()</code> returns
  a <code>Consumable</code> because the system cannot statically analyze which providers will be
  available. The developer must handle async resolution explicitly via <code>await</code> or <code>for await</code>.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>8. import.injector</h2>

<h3>8.1 Concept</h3>
<p>
  <code>import.injector</code> is a proposed special reference (analogous to <code>import.meta</code>)
  that refers to the current module's injector context.
  It is used as a source in <code>provide ... from</code> statements.
</p>
<pre><code>// Inside an injector block
injector AppScope {
  provide * from import.injector;            // re-provide all from module's parent
  provide { 'customElements' } from import.injector; // re-provide specific registries
}</code></pre>

<h3>8.2 The ES Module Singleton Problem</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Challenge:</strong> ES Modules are evaluated once and cached.
  <code>import.meta</code> is per-module, but the module instance is shared across all importers.
  There is no native mechanism for <code>import.injector</code> to resolve differently depending on
  which injector scope loaded the module.
</p>
<p>
  This means <code>import.injector</code> <strong>cannot work as a native runtime construct</strong>.
  It is fundamentally a compile-time concept.
</p>

<h3>8.3 Compile-Time Solution</h3>
<p>A transformer replaces <code>import.injector</code> with a scope-resolution function call:</p>
<pre><code>// Source (DSL)
provide * from import.injector;

// Compiled output
provide * from __resolveInjector(import.meta);
// __resolveInjector uses a WeakMap&lt;ImportMeta, Injector&gt; to look up
// the injector that was active when this module was loaded.</code></pre>
<p>
  The injector binding happens at module initialization time.
  The build tool inserts a registration call at the top of the compiled module:
</p>
<pre><code>// Inserted by transformer
__registerModuleInjector(import.meta, __currentInjector);</code></pre>

<h3>8.4 Runtime Fallback (Factory Pattern)</h3>
<p>
  Without a transformer, modules participate in injection via the
  <code>InjectableModule</code> pattern — a factory function that receives the injector as a parameter:
</p>
<pre><code>// Module exports a factory
export function setup(injector) {
  const parsers = injector.get('customExpressionParsers');
  injector.set('customContexts:state', new AppStore());
}

// Consumer calls the factory with the appropriate scope
import { setup } from './my-module.js';
const myInjector = new ModuleInjector(import.meta);
setup(myInjector);</code></pre>
<p>This is the approach used by the plateau project's <code>InjectableModule</code> class and is the recommended Tier 1 pattern.</p>

<hr>

<h2>9. DOM Integration</h2>

<h3>9.1 Plugged Mode (Node.prototype patches)</h3>
<p>In plugged mode, <code>applyWebInjectorsPatches()</code> adds methods to <code>Node.prototype</code>:</p>

<h4>Injector Traversal</h4>
<table>
  <tr><th>Method</th><th>Signature</th><th>Behavior</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>getOwnInjector()</code></td>
    <td><code>(): HTMLInjector | undefined</code></td>
    <td>Get injector directly attached to this node</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>hasOwnInjector()</code></td>
    <td><code>(): boolean</code></td>
    <td>Check if this node has a direct injector</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>getClosestInjector()</code></td>
    <td><code>(): HTMLInjector | null</code></td>
    <td>Walk up to find nearest injector (own, parent chain, root, creation)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>injectors()</code></td>
    <td><code>(): Generator&lt;HTMLInjector&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Yield all injectors up the chain</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h4>Context Methods (from plateau, not yet ported)</h4>
<table>
  <tr><th>Method</th><th>Signature</th><th>Behavior</th><th>Status</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>getContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string): CustomContext | undefined</code></td>
    <td>Walk injector chain for <code>customContexts:{type}</code></td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>getOwnContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string): CustomContext | null</code></td>
    <td>Check only this element's injector</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>createContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string): CustomContext | undefined</code></td>
    <td>Construct from <code>customContextTypes</code> registry via chain</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>ensureContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string): CustomContext</code></td>
    <td>Get own or create + attach</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>hasContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string): boolean</code></td>
    <td>Boolean check up the chain</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>queryContext()</code></td>
    <td><code>(type: string, query: string): Consumable</code></td>
    <td>Consume with path expression</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>createElement()</code></td>
    <td><code>(tagName: string, options?): Element</code></td>
    <td>Resolve from <code>customElements</code> registries in injector chain</td>
    <td>Not ported</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3>9.2 Unplugged Mode (Static methods)</h3>
<p>All DOM injection operations are available without patches via <code>InjectorRoot</code> static methods:</p>
<pre><code>// Get a specific provider
const provider = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(element, 'customContexts:nav');

// Get all providers available to an element
const providers = InjectorRoot.getProvidersOf(element);

// Walk the full injector chain (generator)
for (const injector of InjectorRoot.getInjectorChain(element)) {
  const value = injector.get('customContexts:state');
  if (value) break;
}

// Lookup by registry entry
const ButtonDef = InjectorRoot.getDefinitionInProviderOf(element, 'customElements', Button);
const localName = InjectorRoot.getLocalNameInProviderOf(element, 'customElements', Button);
const ButtonCls = InjectorRoot.getValueInProviderOf(element, 'customElements', 'my-button');

// Manual injector management
const root = new InjectorRoot();
root.attach(document);
const injector = root.ensureInjector(element);
injector.set('customContexts:state', myStore);</code></pre>

<h3>9.3 HTML Declarative Forms (Deferred to Phase 2)</h3>
<p>These forms require the <code>customScriptTypes</code> registry which is not yet built:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;!-- Script type: injector --&gt;
&lt;script type="injector" name="AppScope"&gt;
  provide AppStore as 'customContexts:state';
  provide Router as 'customContexts:route';
&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- Attribute-based injection --&gt;
&lt;div injector="AppScope"&gt;
  &lt;!-- elements here consume from AppScope --&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- Isolated scope --&gt;
&lt;div injector="Sandbox" isolate&gt;
  &lt;!-- no parent chain --&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>9.4 Creation Injector Context</h3>
<p>
  When elements are created programmatically (e.g., <code>document.createElement()</code>),
  they are not yet attached to the DOM tree and cannot walk the ancestor chain.
  The system handles this via <code>InjectorRoot.creationInjector</code> — a static property
  set before element creation to capture the intended injector scope:
</p>
<pre><code>// Internal mechanism (handled automatically in plugged mode)
InjectorRoot.creationInjector = parentInjector;
const element = document.createElement('my-element');
// element's constructor can access InjectorRoot.creationInjector
InjectorRoot.creationInjector = null;</code></pre>

<hr>

<h2>10. Module Integration</h2>

<h3>10.1 ModuleInjector</h3>
<p>A specialized injector for ES Module scopes. Targets <code>ImportMeta</code> instead of DOM elements.</p>
<pre><code>import { ModuleInjector } from 'web-everything/unplugged';

const moduleInjector = new ModuleInjector(import.meta);
moduleInjector.set('customContexts:config', appConfig);
moduleInjector.set('customElements', myRegistry);</code></pre>

<h3>10.2 InjectableModule</h3>
<p>
  A convenience facade that wraps <code>ModuleInjector</code> with a name, setup callback, and exports tracking.
  This is the recommended Tier 1 pattern for module-level injection.
</p>
<pre><code>import { InjectableModule } from 'web-everything/unplugged';

const module = new InjectableModule('my-module', import.meta, (mod) => {
  // Setup: provide into this module's injector
  mod.provide('customContexts:logger', new Logger());

  // Setup: consume from parent injector
  const config = mod.consume('customContexts:config', import.meta);
});

// Bootstrap triggers the setup function
module.bootstrap();</code></pre>

<h3>10.3 Cross-Scope Bridging</h3>
<p>
  Module injectors and DOM injectors can be connected in a parent-child hierarchy.
  This allows module-level providers to flow into the DOM tree:
</p>
<pre><code>// Module-level injector (provides app-wide dependencies)
const appModule = new ModuleInjector(import.meta);
appModule.set('customContexts:config', appConfig);

// DOM-level injector root (document inherits from module)
const root = new InjectorRoot();
root.attach(document);
const docInjector = root.ensureInjector(document);
docInjector.parentInjector = appModule;

// Now any element in the document can consume 'customContexts:config'
// because the chain traverses: element → ... → document → appModule</code></pre>

<p>
  <strong>Type compatibility note:</strong> <code>HTMLInjector</code> expects querier type <code>Node</code>,
  while <code>ModuleInjector</code> expects querier type <code>ImportMeta</code>.
  When crossing scope boundaries, the <code>isQuerierValid</code> check on the
  <code>ModuleInjector</code> returns <code>true</code> unconditionally, so DOM nodes
  can traverse through it. This is by design — module providers are globally available
  within their scope.
</p>

<h3>10.4 The Module-Element Relationship</h3>
<p>
  A custom element class is defined in a module but lives in a DOM tree.
  These are separate scopes with different injector chains:
</p>
<pre><code>// Module scope: resolved at class definition time
// (via import.injector or InjectableModule)
consume { format } from import.injector;

class MyElement extends HTMLElement {
  // DOM scope: resolved at connection time
  // (via element's ancestor chain)
  connectedCallback() {
    const nav = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(this, 'customContexts:nav');

    // Module-scope values are captured in closure
    this.textContent = format(nav.currentRoute);
  }
}</code></pre>

<hr>

<h2>11. Type System</h2>

<h3>11.1 ProviderTypeMap (Tier 2 — works with standard TypeScript)</h3>
<p>
  The <code>ProviderTypeMap</code> interface maps provider keys to their value types.
  Applications extend it via module augmentation:
</p>
<pre><code>// types/providers.d.ts
declare module 'web-everything' {
  interface ProviderTypeMap {
    'customElements': CustomElementRegistry;
    'customContextTypes': CustomContextRegistry;
    'customAttributes': CustomAttributeRegistry;
    'customContexts:nav': NavigationContext;
    'customContexts:state': AppStore;
    'customContexts:route': RouteContext;
  }
}</code></pre>
<p>This enables typed <code>get()</code>, <code>set()</code>, and <code>consume()</code> calls:</p>
<pre><code>// TypeScript infers the return type from the key
const nav = injector.get('customContexts:nav');
// nav: NavigationContext | undefined

const consumable = injector.consume('customContexts:state', this);
// consumable: Consumable&lt;AppStore&gt;

injector.set('customContexts:nav', new NavigationContext());
// Type-checks: value must be NavigationContext</code></pre>

<h3>11.2 Typed Consume</h3>
<p>When the ProviderTypeMap doesn't cover a key, explicit typing is available:</p>
<pre><code>const consumable = injector.consume&lt;MyService&gt;('custom:my-service', this);
// consumable: Consumable&lt;MyService&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>11.3 Aspirational: <code>declare injector</code> (Deferred)</h3>
<p>
  A TypeScript language extension for declaring typed injector scopes.
  This would require TypeScript team adoption and is not actionable today.
</p>
<pre><code>// Aspirational — requires TS language extension
declare injector AppScope {
  provides: {
    'customContexts:redux': ReduxStore;
    'customElements': CustomElementRegistry;
  }
  consumes: {
    'customContexts:config': AppConfig;
  }
}</code></pre>

<hr>

<h2>12. Tooling Requirements</h2>

<h3>12.1 Tooling Matrix</h3>
