<h3>12.2 No-Tool Path (Phase 1)</h3>
<p>
  The Runtime API (Tier 1) requires <strong>no build tooling</strong>.
  All injector operations use standard JavaScript:
</p>
<pre><code>import { InjectorRoot, HTMLInjector } from 'web-everything/unplugged';

const root = new InjectorRoot();
root.attach(document);

const injector = root.ensureInjector(document.body);
injector.set('customContexts:state', new AppStore());

// Consume
const consumable = injector.consume('customContexts:state', myElement);
const { value } = await consumable;</code></pre>

<h3>12.3 Light-Tool Path (Phase 2)</h3>
<p>
  A Vite/esbuild plugin that detects files with injector DSL
  (by file extension <code>.injector.ts</code> or a pragma comment)
  and transforms them to standard TypeScript before the compiler processes them.
</p>
<pre><code>// vite.config.mts
import { injectorTransform } from 'web-everything/tools';

export default {
  plugins: [
    injectorTransform(),  // transforms .injector.ts files
  ],
};</code></pre>
<p>The plugin would:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Parse the DSL syntax with a JavaScript-based parser</li>
  <li>Transform to Tier 1 runtime API calls</li>
  <li>Generate source maps for debugging</li>
  <li>Return standard TypeScript that esbuild/tsc can process</li>
</ol>

<h3>12.4 Full-Tool Path (Phase 2+)</h3>
<p>
  Full Babel or SWC integration with parser extensions for native
  <code>provide</code>/<code>consume</code>/<code>injector</code> keyword support.
  This is the long-term vision but has the highest implementation cost.
</p>

<h3>12.5 Chrome DevTools Extension</h3>
<p>A Chrome DevTools extension would provide:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Injector Tree panel:</strong> Visualize the injector hierarchy for the inspected element</li>
  <li><strong>Provider inspector:</strong> List all providers on each injector in the chain</li>
  <li><strong>Consumer tracking:</strong> Show which elements are consuming which providers</li>
  <li><strong>Consumable state:</strong> Show pending/resolved/rejected status</li>
</ul>
<p>
  The extension would read injector state from the page via <code>InjectorRoot</code>'s
  static methods, which are accessible from the DevTools console context.
  This is Phase 2+ and non-blocking.
</p>

