<h2>13. Open Questions</h2>

<table>
  <tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Impact</th><th>Current Position</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>1</td>
    <td><strong>Nested provide batch syntax</strong><br><code>provide { { 'B1' } from 'customElements', 'customAttrs' } from import.injector</code></td>
    <td>Syntax complexity</td>
    <td>Deferred — individual statements suffice for Phase 1</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>2</td>
    <td><strong>Fallback resolution chain</strong><br><code>provide { Logger } from A, B;</code> — what if A lacks the provider?</td>
    <td>Design clarity</td>
    <td>First match wins. If A has it, use A. Otherwise try B. Open for discussion.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>3</td>
    <td><strong>Provider disposal</strong><br>When an injector is removed from DOM, what happens to active Consumables?</td>
    <td>Correctness</td>
    <td>Consumable.reject() should be called, causing for-await loops to exit. Needs formalization.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>4</td>
    <td><strong><code>provide class</code> shorthand</strong><br><code>provide class MyButton extends CustomElement { }</code></td>
    <td>Naming convention</td>
    <td>Phase 2 — use PascalCase-to-kebab-case algorithm (split on case boundaries, lowercase, join with hyphens). Single-word class names that produce a tag without a hyphen are a <strong>compile-time error</strong> with a suggested fix. This is safe because <code>provide class</code> is declarative (like <code>import</code>) and processed by the transformer, not at runtime.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>5</td>
    <td><strong>Domain providers (<code>@domain/path</code>)</strong><br>Should <code>@</code>-prefixed keys have special runtime behavior?</td>
    <td>API surface</td>
    <td>Naming convention only in Phase 1. No special runtime handling.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>6</td>
    <td><strong>Decorator integration</strong><br><code>@provide('customContexts:state')</code> on class fields</td>
    <td>DX ergonomics</td>
    <td>Deferred — TC39 decorators still stage 3. Could complement DSL later.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>7</td>
    <td><strong>Cross-scope type compatibility</strong><br>ModuleInjector querier is <code>ImportMeta</code>, HTMLInjector querier is <code>Node</code></td>
    <td>Type safety</td>
    <td>ModuleInjector.isQuerierValid returns true unconditionally. Works but loses type safety at boundary.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

