<h2>Appendix B: Framework Comparison</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Framework</th><th>DI Mechanism</th><th>Scope Model</th><th>Compile-Time?</th><th>Web Everything Parallel</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Angular</strong></td>
    <td><code>@Injectable()</code> + <code>providers[]</code> in modules/components</td>
    <td>Hierarchical (module → component tree)</td>
    <td>Yes — Angular compiler transforms decorators</td>
    <td>Closest analog. Injector hierarchy + provide/consume is similar to Angular's DI.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>React</strong></td>
    <td><code>createContext()</code> + <code>&lt;Context.Provider&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Component tree (ancestor chain)</td>
    <td>No — runtime only</td>
    <td>Context.Provider ≈ <code>injector.set('customContexts:X', value)</code></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Vue</strong></td>
    <td><code>provide()</code> / <code>inject()</code> in Composition API</td>
    <td>Component tree (ancestor chain)</td>
    <td>No — runtime only</td>
    <td>Closest naming match. Vue's provide/inject mirrors the provide/consume pattern.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Solid</strong></td>
    <td>Context via <code>createContext()</code> + <code>&lt;Context.Provider&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Component tree</td>
    <td>Partial — compiler optimizes reactivity</td>
    <td>Consumable's reactive watching parallels Solid's signal-based reactivity.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Lit</strong></td>
    <td><a href="https://lit.dev/docs/data/context/">@lit/context</a> using TC39 Context Protocol</td>
    <td>DOM tree (custom events)</td>
    <td>No — runtime only</td>
    <td>Most aligned with web standards. Uses <code>context-request</code> events on DOM tree.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>Key differentiator:</strong> Web Everything's injector system is <em>registry-aware</em> —
  it doesn't just pass values through a tree, it manages named registries
  (<code>customElements</code>, <code>customAttributes</code>, etc.) with scoped definition/override semantics.
  No other framework combines hierarchical DI with registry management.
</p>

